\begin_layout Standard
In class, we defined the 
\emph on
Kronecker product
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes B$
\end_inset

 of two matrices as the matri 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\otimes B=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{11}B & a_{12}B & \cdots\\
a_{21}B & a_{22}B & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mbox{row }i,\mbox{column }j)$
\end_inset

 entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Derive the following properties of Kronecker products from this definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\otimes B)^{*}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\overline{a_{11}}B^{*} & \overline{a_{21}}B^{*} & \cdots\\
\overline{a_{12}}B^{*} & \overline{a_{22}}B^{*} & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

by swapping rows and columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes B$
\end_inset

 and conjugating.
 By inspection, this is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}\otimes B^{*}$
\end_inset

, since the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{*}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\overline{a_{11}} & \overline{a_{21}} & \cdots\\
\overline{a_{12}} & \overline{a_{22}} & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\otimes B)(C\otimes D)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{11}B & a_{12}B & \cdots\\
a_{21}B & a_{22}B & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
c_{11}D & c_{12}D & \cdots\\
c_{21}D & c_{22}D & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

As shown in class, when we multiply the two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

block
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrices like this, we can use the ordinary 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

row times column
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrix-multiplication formula where we multiply blocks and add them up,
 i.e.
 the product is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{1k}Bc_{k1}D & \sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{1k}Bc_{k2}D & \cdots\\
\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{2k}Bc_{k2}D & \sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{2k}Bc_{k2}D & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

).
 That is, the 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

-th block is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ik}Bc_{kj}D=\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ik}c_{kj}\right)BD=(AC)_{ij}BD
\]

\end_inset

where we have noticed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ik}c_{kj}$
\end_inset

 is simply the formula for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 element of 
\begin_inset Formula $AC$
\end_inset

.
 But this means 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\otimes B)(C\otimes D)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
(AC)_{11}BD & (AC)_{12}BD & \cdots\\
(AC)_{21}BD & (AC)_{22}BD & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right)=(AC)\otimes(BD).
\]

\end_inset

