\begin_layout Plain Layout
Circular systems of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 identical masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and springs 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the angular displacement of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th mass (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{m}=0$
\end_inset

 for all springs when they are at rest).
 Imagine that the springs can move in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 direction, but cannot move in the radial direction (for example, if they
 are sliding without friction on the surface of a cylinder of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that the equation of motion of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th mass is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{\phi}_{n}=\kappa(\phi_{n+1}-\phi_{n})-\kappa(\phi_{n}-\phi_{n-1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\phi}_{n}=\frac{\kappa}{m}(\phi_{n+1}-2\phi_{n}+\phi_{n-1})$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(\begin{array}{ccccccc}
-2 & 1 &  &  &  &  & 1\\
1 & -2 & 1\\
 & 1 & -2 & 1\\
 &  & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  & 1 & -2 & 1\\
 &  &  &  & 1 & -2 & 1\\
1 &  &  &  &  & 1 & -2
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Note the first and last rows! This is a consequence of the periodicity of
 the system, since we can identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}=\phi_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{N+1}=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To check definiteness, the easiest way is to factorize 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Similar to class, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\phi}_{n}$
\end_inset

 in two steps: first we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n+0.5}=\phi_{n+1}-\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

, then we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\phi}_{n}=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(\psi_{n+0.5}-\psi_{n-0.5}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Unlike the 1d case in class, however, there are only 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 values 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n+0.5}$
\end_inset

, equal to the number of springs! Hence, we obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{1.5}\\
\psi_{2.5}\\
\vdots\\
\psi_{N-0.5}\\
\psi_{N+0.5}
\end{array}\right)=D\vec{x}=\left(\begin{array}{ccccc}
-1 & 1\\
 & -1 & 1\\
 &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  & -1 & 1\\
1 &  &  &  & -1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\phi_{1}\\
\phi_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\phi_{N-1}\\
\phi_{N}
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where we must be careful to get the periodicity right for the last row 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{N+0.5}=\phi_{1}-\phi_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\phi}_{1}=\frac{\kappa}{m}(\psi_{1.5}-\psi_{N+0.5})$
\end_inset

, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\vec{x}}=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(\begin{array}{ccccc}
1 &  &  &  & -1\\
-1 & 1\\
 & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  & -1 & 1\\
 &  &  & -1 & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{1.5}\\
\psi_{2.5}\\
\vdots\\
\psi_{N-0.5}\\
\psi_{N+0.5}
\end{array}\right)=-\frac{\kappa}{m}D^{T}D\vec{x},
\]

\end_inset

where we have identified that the matrix to take the differences of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n+0.5}$
\end_inset

 is precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $-D^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=-\frac{\kappa}{m}D^{T}D$
\end_inset

, which by inspection is at least 
\series bold
negative semidefinite
\series default
 (from class).
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

It is 
\series bold
not
\series default
 negative-definite, however.
 This can be checked in a variety of ways, most easily by noticing that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
\vdots\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is not full-rank (and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $RA$
\end_inset

 acts 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 on each of the 
\emph on
columns
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 it permutes each column, giving: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
RA=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(\begin{array}{ccccccc}
1 & -2 & 1\\
 & 1 & -2 & 1\\
 &  & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  & 1 & -2 & 1\\
 &  &  &  & 1 & -2 & 1\\
1 &  &  &  &  & 1 & -2\\
-2 & 1 &  &  &  &  & 1
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $AR=(R^{T}A^{T})^{T}=(R^{T}A)^{T}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to permuting each 
\emph on
row
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{T}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 in the opposite direction), hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{T}A=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(\begin{array}{ccccccc}
1 & -2 & 1\\
 & 1 & -2 & 1\\
 &  & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  & 1 & -2 & 1\\
 &  &  &  & 1 & -2 & 1\\
1 &  &  &  &  & 1 & -2\\
-2 & 1 &  &  &  &  & 1
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

which 
\begin_inset Formula $=RA$
\end_inset

.
 Q.E.D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}=R\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $RA=AR$
\end_inset

, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{y}=AR\vec{x}=RA\vec{x}=\lambda R\vec{x}=\lambda\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 But we were told that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1: this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 must be linearly dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}=\alpha\vec{x}$
\end_inset

