\begin_layout Enumerate
We just write out 
\begin_inset Formula $R\vec{x}=e^{ik}\vec{x}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{N-1}\\
x_{N}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
x_{2}\\
x_{3}\\
\vdots\\
x_{N}\\
1
\end{array}\right)=e^{ik}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{N-1}\\
x_{N}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=e^{ik}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=e^{ik}x_{2}=e^{2ik}$
\end_inset

, and so on, or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{x}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
e^{ik}\\
\vdots\\
e^{i(N-2)k}\\
e^{i(N-1)k}
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

or more simply: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{x_{n}=e^{i(n-1)k}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On an eigenvector, 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{N}\vec{x}=e^{iNk}\vec{x}=\vec{x},$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{iNk}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $Nk$
\end_inset

 is an integer multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Nk=2\pi m$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0,1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

, giving eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\alpha_{m}=e^{i\frac{2\pi m}{N}}}.
\]

\end_inset

A little more carefully, we notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{N}=\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

, so we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 distinct eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{m=0,1,\ldots,N-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now that we know the eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

, we can plug it back into 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{x}=\lambda\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Each row of this equation has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(x_{n+1}-2x_{n}+x_{n-1}\right)=\lambda x_{n}
\]

\end_inset

and plugging in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=e^{ik(n-1)}=e^{ikn}e^{-ik}$
\end_inset

 and dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 gives: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(e^{ik}-2+e^{ik}\right)=\lambda=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left[2\cos(k)-2\right].
\]

\end_inset

Hence, plugging in the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 from above, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\lambda_{m}=\frac{2\kappa}{m}[\cos(2\pi m/N)-1]=-\frac{4\kappa}{m}\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\pi m}{N}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{m=0,1,\ldots,N-1}$
\end_inset

, where we have used the half-angle identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\cos(k)=2\sin^{2}(k/2)$
\end_inset

 to simplify the final expression.
 Note that the eigenvalues are real and 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq0$
\end_inset

 as expected, with exactly one zero eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

